# Media & Storage Policy

## Storage architecture

### S3-compatible object storage is mandatory
- **Local dev:** MinIO (or compatible) via Docker Compose
- **Production:** AWS S3, Cloudflare R2, or equivalent
- **Plugin:** Use `@payloadcms/storage-s3` (or the appropriate Payload storage adapter)

### Payload Media collection
- All images, documents, and downloadable files go through Payload's media collection
- Configure image sizes / thumbnails for common use cases:
  - `thumbnail`: 400px wide (grid views, cards)
  - `poster`: 800px wide (work detail pages)
  - `hero`: 1920px wide (hero sections, full-bleed)
  - `og`: 1200×630px (OpenGraph / social sharing)

## Media strategy by type

### Images (posters, team photos, logos)
- Upload through Payload media collection → stored in S3
- Serve via S3 URLs (or CDN in production)
- Use Next.js `<Image>` with `remotePatterns` configured for S3 bucket
- When migrating: seed scripts should upload existing `public/assets/` images to S3

### Heavy video / trailer content
- Do NOT store large video files in Payload media or S3
- Store video on dedicated platforms (YouTube, Vimeo, or a video CDN)
- In Payload: store the **embed URL / video ID** as a text field
- The `videoUrl` field in the current `MediaItem` type already follows this pattern

### Brand assets (logos, fonts)
- Logos → Payload media collection (seedable, editable)
- Fonts → keep in `public/fonts/` (or S3 if needed for CDN)

## Locale-aware assets

Cinema/media content may have locale-specific assets:

### Pattern: localized media relationships
```typescript
{
  name: 'poster',
  type: 'upload',
  relationTo: 'media',
  localized: true, // different poster per locale
}
```

### When to use locale-aware assets
- Film posters (different artwork by region)
- Key art / marketing materials
- Press kit downloads
- Localized stills or promotional images

### When NOT to localize assets
- Team headshots (same person regardless of locale)
- Brand logos (universal)
- Generic site imagery

## Migration from public/assets/

Current images live in:
- `public/assets/works/` — work/film posters
- `public/assets/posters/` — additional poster variants
- `public/assets/team/` — team member photos
- `public/assets/logos/` — brand logos
- `public/assets/portfolio-medias/` — portfolio/behind-the-scenes
- `public/assets/images/` — general images

During migration:
1. Set up Payload media collection with S3 adapter
2. Seed scripts upload these images to S3 via Payload Local API
3. Update frontend components to use Payload media URLs instead of `/assets/` paths
4. Keep `public/assets/` in place until all references are migrated
5. Remove local copies only after confirming S3-served versions work

## What NOT to do
- Do not store videos as Payload media uploads
- Do not hardcode S3 bucket URLs in components — use Payload media URLs
- Do not skip S3 setup locally ("I'll just use local disk") — MinIO is easy via Docker
- Do not assume a single universal asset per work when locale variants are likely
